s intermingled after 1603, with a variety of consequences, often destabilising. The importance of the Gaelic sphere in Irish-Scottish connections also receives much greater attention here than in previous accounts. This Gaedhealtacht played a central role in the transmission of religious radicalism, both Catholic and Protestant, in Ireland and Scotland, ultimately leading to political crisis and revolution within the British Isles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAtlantic World History.  aBritish history.  aColonialism and colonisation.  aEarly Modern History.  aIrish history.  aReformation and Counter-Reformation Studies.  aReligious Missions.  aScottish history.  aThree Kingdoms History.  aUlster Plantation.1 aArmstrong, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuignan, Aoife, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEgan, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFord, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMac Cuarta SJ, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhlmeyer, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoulston, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpurlock, R. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org